{"title_page": "John Mitchell (chemist)", "text_new": "{{short description|American chemist and researcher}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = John F Mitchell\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| alma_mater         = Cornell University (BA), University of Chicago (PhD)\n| awards             = University of Chicago Distinguished Performance Award (2006)\n<br>Presidential Early Career Award for Scientists and Engineers (2000)<br /> Department of Energy Early Career Award (1999)\n| organization       = [https://www.anl.gov/ Argonne National Laboratory]\n| website            = https://www.anl.gov/profile/john-mitchell\n}}'''John F. Mitchell''' is an American [[chemist]] and researcher. He is the Associate Director<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/profile/john-mitchell|title=John Mitchell|website=www.anl.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> of the Materials Science Division at the [[U.S. Department of Energy]]\u2019s (DOE) [[Argonne National Laboratory]] and leads Argonne's Emerging Materials Group.\n\nMitchell's expertise is in the discovery, synthesis, crystal growth, and study of quantum materials, including correlated electron oxides, quantum magnets, and topological matter. He has authored or co-authored over 320 peer-reviewed articles in scholarly journals.\n\nMitchell is an Argonne Distinguished Fellow and is<ref name=\":0\" />  a fellow of the American Physical Society, and a member of the American Physical Society, American Association for the Advancement of Science, and the Materials Research Society.  He served in the Chair line of the Division of Materials Physics of the American Physical Society from 2013\u20132017.\n\n==Early life and education==\nMitchell received<ref name=\":0\" />  his A.B. degree ''summa cum laude'' in Chemistry from [[Cornell University]] in 1987, and his Ph.D. in Chemistry from the University of Chicago in 1993 for theoretical studies of defect structures and order-disorder transitions of early transition metal chalcogenides.\n\nMitchell joined<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/system/files/2020-03/Curriculum%20Vitae_03162020.pdf|title=John F Mitchell Curriculum Vitae|url-status=live}}</ref> Argonne as a DOE Distinguished Postdoctoral Fellow in 1993. He went on to become<ref name=\":1\" /> a Senior Chemist in 2009. Mitchell became<ref name=\":1\" /> Associate Director of the Materials Science Division in 2012 and served as Division Director from 2017\u20132019. Mitchell is also an adjunct professor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://materials.ucsb.edu/people/adjunct-and-distinguished-faculty/john-mitchell|title=John Mitchell|website=materials.ucsb.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> in the Materials Science and Engineering Department of the University of California, Santa Barbara.\n\n==Research==\nMitchell's research focuses on strategic synthesis, crystal growth, and structural studies of correlated electron transition metal oxides and [[chalcogenides]], principally using neutron and x-ray scattering. He has coordinated the development team for a high-resolution powder diffractometer at the Advanced Photon Source, and led Argonne's strategic initiative in Materials and Molecular Design and Discovery. Mitchell has also led a project study in the DOE Center of Excellence for the Synthesis and Processing of Advanced Materials, entitled, \u201cSpin Polarized Transport in Complex Oxides.\u201d\n\nEarly in his career, Mitchell focused on understanding the electronic and magnetic properties of 2D manganese oxides that exhibit colossal magnetoresistance (CMR).  Among several key findings,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Campbell|first=B.J.|last2=Osborn|first2=R.|last3=Argyriou|first3=D.N.|last4=Vasiliu-Doloc|first4=L.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Sinha|first6=S.K.|last7=Ruett|first7=U.|last8=Ling|first8=C.D.|last9=Islam|first9=Z.|last10=Lynn|first10=J.W.|title=Structure of nanoscale polaron correlations in La1.2Sr1.8Mn2O7,|journal=Phys. Rev. B|date=2002|language=en|volume=65|doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.65.014427|arxiv=cond-mat/0106477}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Sun|first=Z.|last2=Chuang|first2=YD.|last3=Fedorov|first3=A.V.|last4=Douglas|first4=J.F.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Reznik|first6=D.|last7=Weber|first7=F.|last8=Aliouane|first8=N.|last9=Argyriou|first9=D.N.|last10=Zheng|first10=H.|last11=Kimura|first11=T.|last12=Tokura|first12=Y|last13=Revcolevschi|first13=A.|last14=Dessau|first14=D.S|title=Quasiparticlelike peaks, kinks, and electron-phonon coupling at the (\u03c0, 0) regions in the CMR oxide La2-2xSr1+2xMn2O7|journal=Phys. Rev. lett.|language=en|date=2006|volume=97|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.97.056401|arxiv=cond-mat/0510255}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Mannella|first=N.|last2=Yang|first2=W.L.|last3=Zhou|first3=X.J.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Zaanen|first6=J.|last7=Devereaux|first7=T.P.|last8=Nagaosa|first8=N.|last9=Hussain|first9=Z.|last10=Shen|first10=Z.X.|title=Polaronic orbital polarization in a layered colossal magnetoresistive manganite|journal=Phys. Rev. B|language=en|date=2003|volume=67|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevB.67.020409}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Campbell|first=B.J.|last2=Sinha|first2=S.K.|last3=Osborn|first3=R.|last4=Rosenkranz|first4=S.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Argyriou|first6=D.N.|last7=Vasiliu-Doloc|first7=L.|last8=Seeck|first8=O.H.|last9=Lynn|first9=J.W.|title=Nodal quasiparticle in pseudogapped colossal magnetoresistive manganites|journal=Nature|language=en|date=2005|volume=438|pages=474\u2013478|DOI=10.1038/nature04273|hdl=1887/5127|hdl-access=free}}</ref> Mitchell's work directly led to the widespread understanding of local polaronic distortions and the \u2018melting\u2019 of their short-range correlations as a mechanism behind the CMR effect.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Vasiliu-Doloc|first=L.|last2=Rosenkranz|first2=S.|last3=Osborn|first3=R.|last4=Sinha|first4=S.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Lynn|first6=J.W.|last7=Mesot|first7=J.|last8=Seeck|first8=O.H.|last9=Lee|first9=W-K|last10=Preosti|first10=G.|last11=Fedro|first11=A.J.|url=https://www.aps.anl.gov/APS-Science-Highlight/2000-06-28/charge-melting-polaron-collapse-in-la12sr18mn207|title=Charge Melting and Polaron Collapse in La1.2Sr1.8Mn2O7|journal=Phys. Rev. Lett.|language=en|date=1999|volume=83|issue=21|pages=4393\u20134396|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.83.4393}}</ref>\n\nTurning to heavy transition metals, Mitchell explored the behavior of iridium based oxides in which electron correlation and spin-orbit coupling meet on similar energy scales.  Mitchell's group discovered evidence for electronic and magnetic properties in these systems that parallel those found in high-temperature copper oxide superconductors.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Y.K.|last2=Krupin|first2=O.|last3=Denlinger|first3=J.D.|last4=Bostwick|first4=A.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Rotenberg|first6=E.|last7=Zhao|first7=Q.|last8=Allen|first8=J.W.|last9=Kim|first9=B.J.|url=https://www.anl.gov/argonne-scientific-publications/pub/103141|title=Fermi Arcs in a Doped Pseudospin-1/2 Heisenberg Antiferromagnet|journal=Science|language=en|date=1999|volume=83|issue=21|issn=0036-8075|pages=4393\u20134396|DOI=10.1126/science.1251151|arxiv=1406.4489}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Jungho|last2=Casa|first2=D.|last3=Upton|first3=1 M. H.|last4=Gog|first4=T.|last5=Kim|first5=Young-June|last6=Veenendaal|first6=M. van|last7=Daghofer|first7=M.|last8=van den Brink|first8=J.|last9=Khaliullin|first9=G.|last10=Kim|first10=B.J.|title=Magnetic Excitation Spectra of Sr2IrO4 Probed by Resonant Inelastic X-Ray Scattering: Establishing Links to Cuprate Superconductors|journal=Phys. Rev. Lett|language=en|date=2012|volume=108|issue=17|issn=1079-7114|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.177003|doi-access=free}}</ref>  Mitchell's group also found direct evidence of bond-directional anisotropy in the candidate quantum spin liquid Na<sub>2</sub>IrO<sub>3</sub>, validating the dominant role of this interaction.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Chun|first=S.H.|last2=Kim|first2=J-W|last3=Kim|first3=J.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Malliakas|first5=C.|last6=Stoumpos|first6=C.|last7=Mehlawat|first7=K.|last8=Singh|first8=Y.|last9=Choi|first9=Y.|last10=Gog|first10=T.|last11=Al-Zein|first11=A.|last12=Moretti Sala|first12=M.|last13=Krisch|first13=M.|last14=Chaloupka|first14=J.|last15=Jackeli|first15=G.|last16=Khaliullin|first16=G.|last17=Kim|first17=B.J.|last18=Mitchel|first18=J.F|title=Direct Evidence for Dominant Bond-directional Interactions in a Honeycomb Lattice Iridate Na2IrO3|journal=Nature Physics|language=en|date=2015|volume=11|issue=17|issn=1079-7114|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.177003|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nMitchell then discovered routes to grow single crystals of two-dimensional nickel oxides that, like the iridium systems, mimic cuprate superconductors.  In a series of papers he and his group showed that these nickel oxides exhibit stripe phases, intertwined density waves, and strong in-plane orbital polarization believed to be key to superconductivity.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=J.|last2=Pajerowski|first2=D.|last3=Botana|first3=A.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Harriger|first5=L.|last6=Rodriguez-Rivera|first6=J.|last7=Ruff|first7=J.|last8=Schreiber|first8=N.|last9=Wang|first9=B.|last10=Chen|first10=Y.|last11=Chen|first11=W.|last12=Norman|first12=M.|last13=Rosenkranz|first13=S.|last14=Phelan|first14=D.|last15=Mitchel|first15=J.F|title=Spin Stripe Order in a Square Planar Trilayer Nickelate|journal=Phys. Rev. Lett.|language=en|date=2019|volume=122|issue=24|issn=1079-7114|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.122.247201|arxiv=1903.03246}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=J.|last2=Shen|first2=Y.S.|last3=Norman|first3=M.R.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Mitchel|first5=J.F|title=Stacked charge stripes in the trilayer nickelate La4Ni3O8|journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci.|language=en|date=2016|volume=113|issue=32|pages=8945\u20138950|issn=1091-6490|DOI=10.1073/pnas.1606637113|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=J.|last2=Botana|first2=A.S.|last3=Freeland|first3=J.W.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Mitchel|first5=J.F|last6=Phelan|first6=D|last7=Pardo|first7=V|last8=Norman|first8=M.|title=Large Orbital Polarization in a Metallic Square-Planar Nickelate|journal=Nature Physics |language=en|date=2017|volume=13|pages=864\u2013869|issn=1745-2481|DOI=10.1038/nphys4149|arxiv=1705.00563}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n*Argonne Distinguished Fellow<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/pse/awards-recognition|title=Physical Sciences and Engineering Awards and Recognition|website=www.anl.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*Fellow of the American Physical Society<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aps.org/programs/honors/fellowships/archive-all.cfm?initial=&year=&unit_id=&institution=Argonne+National+Laboratory|title=APS Fellow Archive|website=www.www.aps.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*Member of the American Physical Society, American Crystallographic Society, Materials Research Society, and American Chemical Society\n*Former fellow of the University of Chicago Institute for Molecular Engineering, 2015-2017\n*[[Presidential Early Career Award for Scientists and Engineers]], 2000\n*Department of Energy Outstanding Young Investigator Award, 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clintonwhitehouse4.archives.gov/WH/EOP/OSTP/html/00413_2.html|title=President honors outstanding young scientist|website=clintonwhitehouse4.archives.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitchell, John}}\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American chemists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American chemist and researcher}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = John F Mitchell\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| alma_mater         = Cornell University (BA), University of California, Santa Barbara (PhD)\n| awards             = University of Chicago Distinguished Performance Award (2006)\n<br>Presidential Early Career Award for Scientists and Engineers (2000)<br /> Department of Energy Early Career Award (1999)\n| organization       = [https://www.anl.gov/ Argonne National Laboratory]\n| website            = https://www.anl.gov/profile/john-mitchell\n}}'''John F. Mitchell''' is an American [[chemist]] and researcher. He is the Associate Director<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/profile/john-mitchell|title=John Mitchell|website=www.anl.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> of the Materials Science Division at the [[U.S. Department of Energy]]\u2019s (DOE) [[Argonne National Laboratory]] and leads Argonne's Emerging Materials Group.\n\nMitchell's expertise is in the discovery, synthesis, crystal growth, and study of quantum materials, including correlated electron oxides, quantum magnets, and topological matter. He has authored or co-authored over 320 peer-reviewed articles in scholarly journals.\n\nMitchell is an Argonne Distinguished Fellow and is<ref name=\":0\" />  a fellow of the American Physical Society, and a member of the American Physical Society, American Association for the Advancement of Science, Materials Research Society, and the American Chemical Society.  He served in the Chair line of the Division of Materials Physics of the American Physical Society from 2013\u20132017.\n\n==Early life and education==\nMitchell received<ref name=\":0\" />  his A.B. degree in Chemistry from [[Cornell University]] in 1987, and his Ph.D. in Chemistry from the University of Chicago in 1993 for theoretical studies of defect structures and order-disorder transitions of early transition metal chalcogenides.\n\nMitchell joined<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/system/files/2020-03/Curriculum%20Vitae_03162020.pdf|title=John F Mitchell Curriculum Vitae|url-status=live}}</ref> Argonne as a DOE Distinguished Postdoctoral Fellow in 1993. He went on to become<ref name=\":1\" /> a Senior Chemist in 2009. Mitchell became<ref name=\":1\" /> Associate Director of the Materials Science Division in 2012 and served as Division Director from 2017\u20132019. Mitchell is also an adjunct professor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://materials.ucsb.edu/people/adjunct-and-distinguished-faculty/john-mitchell|title=John Mitchell|website=materials.ucsb.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> in the Materials Science and Engineering Department of the University of California, Santa Barbara.\n\n==Research==\nMitchell's research focuses on strategic synthesis, crystal growth, and structural studies of correlated electron transition metal oxides and [[chalcogenides]], principally using neutron and x-ray scattering. He has coordinated the development team for a high-resolution powder diffractometer at the Advanced Photon Source, and led Argonne's strategic initiative in Materials and Molecular Design and Discovery. Mitchell has also led a project study in the DOE Center of Excellence for the Synthesis and Processing of Advanced Materials, entitled, \u201cSpin Polarized Transport in Complex Oxides.\u201d\n\nEarly in his career, Mitchell focused on understanding the electronic and magnetic properties of 2D manganese oxides that exhibit colossal magnetoresistance (CMR).  Among several key findings,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Campbell|first=B.J.|last2=Osborn|first2=R.|last3=Argyriou|first3=D.N.|last4=Vasiliu-Doloc|first4=L.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Sinha|first6=S.K.|last7=Ruett|first7=U.|last8=Ling|first8=C.D.|last9=Islam|first9=Z.|last10=Lynn|first10=J.W.|title=Stru